<subSubSection id="63CB0AAA2D1AFFFC0FFC7BE13C63FC24" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="2B6E59212D1AFFFC0FFC7BE13C63FC24" blockId="13.[151,1436,261,2027]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis id="19A585332D1AFFFC0FFC7BE13B26FC43" bold="true" box="[198,527,918,944]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Distribution and Habitat:</emphasis>
—This tiny bromeliad was observed growing on quartzite rocks, vertically attached on small cavities, and in rocky fields at 
<quantity id="EC29F4C42D1AFFFC0DE87BCA3A41FC24" box="[722,872,957,983]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.13" metricValueMax="1.4" metricValueMin="0.86" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" unit="m" value="1130.0" valueMax="1400.0" valueMin="860.0">860–1400 m</quantity>
, so far this area is restricted to the PERP.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="63CB0AAA2D1AFFFC0FFC7B943863FBD7" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="2B6E59212D1AFFFC0FFC7B943863FBD7" blockId="13.[151,1436,261,2027]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis id="19A585332D1AFFFC0FFC7B94387EFC0E" bold="true" box="[198,343,995,1021]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Etymology:</emphasis>
—The epithet refers to the small size of the plant, derived from the Greek µƖκρoς, ‘micros’ meaning small.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="63CB0AAA2D1AFFFC0FFC7C463D1EF8A3" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="2B6E59212D1AFFFC0FFC7C463D1EF8A3" blockId="13.[151,1436,261,2027]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<taxonomicName id="ECD122A22D1AFFFC0FFC7C463886FBB9" authorityName="Louzada, Wand. &amp; Versieux. A. Habit. B. Primary" authorityYear="2010" box="[198,431,1073,1098]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Cryptanthus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="micrus">
<emphasis id="19A585332D1AFFFC0FFC7C463886FBB9" box="[198,431,1073,1098]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Cryptanthus micrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinct due to its smaller size and tiny habit when compared to all other species in the genus. It is morphologically similar to xerophytic species belonging to subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="ECD122A22D1AFFFC0BB07C2F380BFB6B" authority="Mez (1891: 202)" authorityName="Mez" authorityPageNumber="202" authorityYear="1891" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Hoplocryptanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="19A585332D1AFFFC0BB07C2F3C76FB82" box="[1162,1375,1112,1137]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Hoplocryptanthus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="4F4024D02D1AFFFC0A527C2F380BFB6B" author="Mez, C." pageId="13" pageNumber="14" pagination="173 - 280" refId="ref7454" refString="Mez, C. (1891) Bromeliaceae. In: Martius, C. F. P., Eichler, A. G. &amp; Urban, I. (Eds). Flora brasiliensis, vol. 3, pars. 3. Frid. Fleischer in comm., Lipsiae, pp. 173 - 280." type="book chapter" year="1891">Mez (1891: 202)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, which is characterized by the presence of leaves that are not constricted above the leaf sheath and by the presence of well developed prickles (
<bibRefCitation id="4F4024D02D1AFFFC0D8A7CD23A06FB4C" author="Mez, C." box="[688,815,1189,1215]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" pagination="173 - 280" refId="ref7454" refString="Mez, C. (1891) Bromeliaceae. In: Martius, C. F. P., Eichler, A. G. &amp; Urban, I. (Eds). Flora brasiliensis, vol. 3, pars. 3. Frid. Fleischer in comm., Lipsiae, pp. 173 - 280." type="book chapter" year="1891">Mez 1891</bibRefCitation>
). According to 
<bibRefCitation id="4F4024D02D1AFFFC0CD47CD23C3CFB4C" author="Ramirez-Morillo, I. M." box="[1006,1301,1189,1215]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" refId="ref7620" refString="Ramirez-Morillo, I. M. (1996) Systematics, phylogeny, chromosome number and evolution of Cryptanthus (Bromeliaceae). Ph. D. thesis, University of Missouri, Saint Louis, Missouri, EUA, 268 pp." type="book" year="1996">Ramírez-Morillo (1996)</bibRefCitation>
, additional characters of this subgenus would include the leaf blades covered in trichomes, fragrant bisexual flowers and broad petals. Species belonging to this subgenus occur more commonly in rocky field vegetation at higher elevations (above 
<quantity id="EC29F4C42D1AFFFC0E517D6E389FFAC0" box="[363,438,1305,1331]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" unit="m" value="800.0">800 m</quantity>
) in exposed places on well-drained substrates (
<bibRefCitation id="4F4024D02D1AFFFC0CE67D6E3DC3FAC0" author="Ramirez-Morillo, I. M." box="[988,1258,1305,1331]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" refId="ref7620" refString="Ramirez-Morillo, I. M. (1996) Systematics, phylogeny, chromosome number and evolution of Cryptanthus (Bromeliaceae). Ph. D. thesis, University of Missouri, Saint Louis, Missouri, EUA, 268 pp." type="book" year="1996">Ramírez-Morillo 1996</bibRefCitation>
). Two endemic species of the 
<taxonomicName id="ECD122A22D1AFFFC0E7D7D373B11FAA9" authority="Plateau" authorityName="Plateau (Libon" authorityYear="1857" box="[327,568,1344,1370]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Podostemaceae" genus="Diamantina" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Diamantina Plateau</taxonomicName>
, that belong to subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="ECD122A22D1AFFFC0C4B7D373D62FAAA" authorityName="Mez" authorityYear="1891" box="[881,1099,1344,1369]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Hoplocryptanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="19A585332D1AFFFC0C4B7D373D62FAAA" box="[881,1099,1344,1369]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Hoplocryptanthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, namely 
<taxonomicName id="ECD122A22D1AFFFC0B847D373876FA73" authority="Rauh (1988: 68)" authorityName="Rauh" authorityPageNumber="68" authorityYear="1988" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Cryptanthus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="leopoldohorstii">
<emphasis id="19A585332D1AFFFC0B847D373CB5FAAA" box="[1214,1436,1344,1369]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">C. leopoldohorstii</emphasis>
Rauh (1988: 68)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="ECD122A22D1AFFFC0EA77D103A3DFA73" authority="Pereira (1978: 252)" authorityName="Pereira" authorityPageNumber="252" authorityYear="1978" box="[413,788,1382,1408]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Cryptanthus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="warasii">
<emphasis id="19A585332D1AFFFC0EA77D103B34FA73" box="[413,541,1383,1408]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">C. warasii</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="4F4024D02D1AFFFC0D1C7D113A3DFA73" author="Pereira, E." box="[550,788,1382,1408]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" pagination="251 - 254" refId="ref7727" refString="Pereira, E. (1978) Species Novae in brasilia bromeliacearum - XI. Bradea 2: 251 - 254." type="journal article" year="1978">Pereira (1978: 252)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
seem to be the morphological closest relatives of 
<emphasis id="19A585332D1AFFFC0ABA7D1039DBFA55" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<taxonomicName id="ECD122A22D1AFFFC0ABA7D1039C7FA55" authorityName="Louzada, Wand. &amp; Versieux. A. Habit. B. Primary" authorityYear="2010" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Cryptanthus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="micrus">C. micrus</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
While reviewing the genus, 
<bibRefCitation id="4F4024D02D1AFFFC0D607DFA3AADFA54" author="Ramirez-Morillo, I. M." box="[602,900,1421,1447]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" refId="ref7620" refString="Ramirez-Morillo, I. M. (1996) Systematics, phylogeny, chromosome number and evolution of Cryptanthus (Bromeliaceae). Ph. D. thesis, University of Missouri, Saint Louis, Missouri, EUA, 268 pp." type="book" year="1996">Ramírez-Morillo (1996)</bibRefCitation>
noticed the proximity of these two species together with 
<taxonomicName id="ECD122A22D1AFFFC0E017DC33A3FFA3D" authority="Leme &amp; Gross (1992: 12)" authorityName="Leme &amp; Gross" authorityPageNumber="12" authorityYear="1992" box="[315,790,1460,1486]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Cryptanthus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="caracensis">
<emphasis id="19A585332D1AFFFC0E017DC338F2FA3E" box="[315,475,1460,1485]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">C. caracensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="4F4024D02D1AFFFC0EDE7DC33A3FFA3D" author="Leme, E. M. C. &amp; Gross, E." box="[484,790,1460,1486]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" pagination="12 - 17" refId="ref7256" refString="Leme, E. M. C. &amp; Gross, E. (1992) A new endemic species from the natural park of Caraca, Minas Gerais state. Cryptanthus Society Journal 7: 12 - 17." type="journal article" year="1992">Leme &amp; Gross (1992: 12)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and proposed to create a new section to include these, based on the presence of stiff succulent leaves with serrate or dentate margins that are densely covered with white or argent trichomes. However the new taxon can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="ECD122A22D1AFFFC0B8F7E763C43F9E9" authorityName="Leme &amp; Gross" authorityYear="1992" box="[1205,1386,1537,1562]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Cryptanthus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="caracensis">
<emphasis id="19A585332D1AFFFC0B8F7E763C43F9E9" box="[1205,1386,1537,1562]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">C. caracensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="ECD122A22D1AFFFC0A457E763878F9B2" authorityName="Rauh" authorityYear="1988" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Cryptanthus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="leopoldohorstii">
<emphasis id="19A585332D1AFFFC0A457E763878F9B2" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">C. leopoldohorstii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="ECD122A22D1AFFFC0E587E5F38C8F9B2" authorityName="Pereira" authorityYear="1978" box="[354,481,1576,1601]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Cryptanthus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="warasii">
<emphasis id="19A585332D1AFFFC0E587E5F38C8F9B2" box="[354,481,1576,1601]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">C. warasii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and from 
<taxonomicName id="ECD122A22D1AFFFC0D507E5F3D3AF9B1" authority="Mez (1891: 203)" authorityName="Mez" authorityPageNumber="203" authorityYear="1891" box="[618,1043,1576,1602]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Cryptanthus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="schwackeanus">
<emphasis id="19A585332D1AFFFC0D507E5F3A15F9B2" box="[618,828,1576,1601]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">C. schwackeanus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="4F4024D02D1AFFFC0C7F7E5F3D3AF9B1" author="Mez, C." box="[837,1043,1576,1602]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" pagination="173 - 280" refId="ref7454" refString="Mez, C. (1891) Bromeliaceae. In: Martius, C. F. P., Eichler, A. G. &amp; Urban, I. (Eds). Flora brasiliensis, vol. 3, pars. 3. Frid. Fleischer in comm., Lipsiae, pp. 173 - 280." type="book chapter" year="1891">Mez (1891: 203)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
that occurs further south, by its shorter and narrower leaf blades and free sepals (vs. connate in different degrees). The indumentum that covers the leaves of 
<taxonomicName id="ECD122A22D1AFFFC0EA87E023B21F97D" authorityName="Louzada, Wand. &amp; Versieux. A. Habit. B. Primary" authorityYear="2010" box="[402,520,1653,1678]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Cryptanthus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="micrus">
<emphasis id="19A585332D1AFFFC0EA87E023B21F97D" box="[402,520,1653,1678]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">C. micrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is sparser when compared to the dense layer of trichomes that covers both surfaces of 
<taxonomicName id="ECD122A22D1AFFFC0E187EEB38B7F946" authorityName="Pereira" authorityYear="1978" box="[290,414,1692,1717]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Cryptanthus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="warasii">
<emphasis id="19A585332D1AFFFC0E187EEB38B7F946" box="[290,414,1692,1717]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">C. warasii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName id="ECD122A22D1AFFFC0E947EEB3BB2F946" authorityName="Louzada, Wand. &amp; Versieux. A. Habit. B. Primary" authorityYear="2010" box="[430,667,1692,1717]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Cryptanthus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="micrus">
<emphasis id="19A585332D1AFFFC0E947EEB3BB2F946" box="[430,667,1692,1717]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Cryptanthus micrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has prickles that are laterally compressed and covered by white trichomes and its leaf margins are dentate. 
<taxonomicName id="ECD122A22D1AFFFC0DAC7EB43A87F92F" authorityName="Leme &amp; Gross" authorityYear="1992" box="[662,942,1731,1756]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Cryptanthus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="caracensis">
<emphasis id="19A585332D1AFFFC0DAC7EB43A87F92F" box="[662,942,1731,1756]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Cryptanthus caracensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="ECD122A22D1AFFFC0C847EB43DBCF92F" authorityName="Rauh" authorityYear="1988" box="[958,1173,1731,1756]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Cryptanthus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="leopoldohorstii">
<emphasis id="19A585332D1AFFFC0C847EB43DBCF92F" box="[958,1173,1731,1756]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">C. leopoldohorstii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="ECD122A22D1AFFFC0BEA7EB43CB2F92F" authorityName="Mez" authorityYear="1891" box="[1232,1435,1731,1756]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Cryptanthus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="schwackeanus">
<emphasis id="19A585332D1AFFFC0BEA7EB43CB2F92F" box="[1232,1435,1731,1756]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">C. schwackeanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
all have serrate margins with shorter prickles. The leaves of 
<taxonomicName id="ECD122A22D1AFFFC0C537E9E3AF4F8F1" authorityName="Louzada, Wand. &amp; Versieux. A. Habit. B. Primary" authorityYear="2010" box="[873,989,1769,1794]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Cryptanthus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="micrus">
<emphasis id="19A585332D1AFFFC0C537E9E3AF4F8F1" box="[873,989,1769,1794]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">C. micrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are somewhat succulent, the prickles are well separated and in cross section the blade is almost planar, while in 
<taxonomicName id="ECD122A22D1AFFFC0CC17F673DB3F8DA" authorityName="Leme &amp; Gross" authorityYear="1992" box="[1019,1178,1808,1833]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Cryptanthus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="caracensis">
<emphasis id="19A585332D1AFFFC0CC17F673DB3F8DA" box="[1019,1178,1808,1833]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">C. caracensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="ECD122A22D1AFFFC0BE87F673CB2F8DA" authorityName="Mez" authorityYear="1891" box="[1234,1435,1808,1833]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Cryptanthus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="schwackeanus">
<emphasis id="19A585332D1AFFFC0BE87F673CB2F8DA" box="[1234,1435,1808,1833]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">C. schwackeanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the prickles are more densely arranged and the blades are clearly canaliculated.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="63CB0AAA2D1AFFFF0FFC7F2A3A50FE80" lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="15" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="conservation">
<paragraph id="2B6E59212D1AFFFF0FFC7F2A3A50FE80" blockId="13.[151,1436,261,2027]" lastBlockId="14.[151,1437,152,371]" lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="15" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis id="19A585332D1AFFFC0FFC7F2A385EF884" bold="true" box="[198,375,1885,1911]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Conservation:</emphasis>
—In 
<collectingRegion id="E91597C32D1AFFFC0E8C7F2A3B7CF884" box="[438,597,1885,1911]" country="Brazil" name="Minas Gerais" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Minas Gerais</collectingRegion>
the genus 
<taxonomicName id="ECD122A22D1AFFFC0DE37F2A3A43F885" box="[729,874,1885,1910]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Cryptanthus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="19A585332D1AFFFC0DE37F2A3A43F885" box="[729,874,1885,1910]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Cryptanthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is threatened due to its species’ narrow ranges and endemism (
<bibRefCitation id="4F4024D02D1AFFFC0E607FF33BA3F86D" author="Versieux, L. M. &amp; Wendt, T." box="[346,650,1924,1950]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" pagination="2989 - 3009" refId="ref8232" refString="Versieux, L. M. &amp; Wendt, T. (2007) Bromeliaceae diversity and conservation in Minas Gerais, Brazil. Biodiversity and Conservation 16: 2989 - 3009." type="journal article" year="2007">Versieux &amp; Wendt 2007</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="ECD122A22D1AFFFC0D9A7FF33ABAF86E" authorityName="Louzada, Wand. &amp; Versieux. A. Habit. B. Primary" authorityYear="2010" box="[672,915,1924,1949]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Cryptanthus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="micrus">
<emphasis id="19A585332D1AFFFC0D9A7FF33ABAF86E" box="[672,915,1924,1949]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Cryptanthus micrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a rare species that has only two known populations in the PERP, all with small numbers of individuals. Based on the IUCN criteria (
<bibRefCitation id="4F4024D02D1AFFFC0BD97FDC3C58F836" author="IUCN &amp; Cambridge, UK" box="[1251,1393,1963,1989]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" refId="ref7121" refString="IUCN (2001) IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria: Version 3.1. IUCN Species Survival Commission. IUCN, Gland, Switzerland and Cambridge, UK." type="book" year="2001">IUCN 2001</bibRefCitation>
) 
<taxonomicName id="ECD122A22D1AFFFC0ABB7FDC39CEF819" authorityName="Louzada, Wand. &amp; Versieux. A. Habit. B. Primary" authorityYear="2010" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Cryptanthus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="micrus">
<emphasis id="19A585332D1AFFFC0ABB7FDC39CEF819" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">C. micrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the conservation status of Critically Endangered CR B1ab(ii,iii) due its restricted occurrence, the small population sizes and decline in the quality of the habitat, taking into consideration that one population is located right along the border of the park. We suggest that studies in the biology of this species should be carried out in order to understand its reproductive strategies to assure its conservation. The lithophytic life 
<taxonomicName id="ECD122A22D19FFFF0FAD797B3818FED5" box="[151,305,268,294]" form="enables" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" rank="form">form enables</taxonomicName>
the species to escape from fires, which are quite frequent in these grassland habitats. To avoid other risks, particularly those of with commercial collectors and bromeliad hunters, we suggest that these populations should be well monitored by the PERP authorities.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
